<div class="section">
  <p class="text-heading-2">Reflection</p>
  <p class="text-body">As a naive <strong>fresher with zero experience interning remotely in the midst of a global pandemic</strong>, it was reassuring to meet my mentors daily during our one-on-one catchups. I’d also present my work to the UX team every week. This helped course-correct while taking advantage of the enormous freedom to explore tangents.  </p>
  <p class="text-body">I had <strong>no experience of Business Intelligence software or financial use-cases.</strong> Luckily, my mentors were ever-patient with my unending stream of basic doubts. A huge (slow) learning for me was how communication in a corporate context can be optimised — by sending agendas before daily catch-ups, prioritising the discussion flow, being alert to nuanced/ layered feedback, and summarising my understanding at the end. I also had the important personal realisation that I prefer mornings for heads-down work time, and later in the day for meetings. My mentors were accommodative, and I scheduled our catchups accordingly. </p>
  <p class="text-body"> Ultimately, though, I did find it <strong>empowering to take control of my project and defend my decisions.</strong> I learnt that ‘I liked this…’ or ‘I felt like…’ usually wouldn’t cut it as an argument. Eventually, scheduling my own meetings and explaining my work to stakeholders gave me a certain sense of autonomy. I slowly felt less need for an explicit ‘go-ahead’ from my mentors, and began making choices based on documented reasoning and assumptions. </p>
  <p class="text-body">
